english:
  title: A Record of the South Tower at Biok County Pavilion
  author: Ha Ryun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Park Seo-saeng, who ranked third in the state examination and now serves as Right Censor and Director of the Royal Secretariat, came to bid me farewell before returning to his native place to tend his ancestors' graves. He entreated me, saying: "Our county of Biok has long been subject to Sangju, yet lies more than sixty leagues distant. Our county clerks must journey five days to receive orders from the prefecture, always hastening, forever fearing they arrive too late. And yet delays occur. When prefecture officials visit, they heap abuse upon our clerks and scatter ruin among our people—sorrows too numerous to recount. In the waning days of the former dynasty, calamities multiplied and our county's fortune declined daily. But our present sovereign, understanding the root of this suffering, has appointed a Supervising Magistrate to each distant county, granting them autonomy. Our humble place too received such an official, and from that moment both clerks and common folk have found relief.

    In the spring of the Year of the Black Sheep, Magistrate Yu Yang arrived and set about restoring all that had fallen to ruin. One day he gathered the elders and spoke thus: 'A county pavilion exists to receive the king's emissaries and proclaim his virtue. Yet our county, no longer as it was, shows forth a structure so cramped and low that when summer's heat arrives, we cannot properly shelter these honored guests. Should not we elders feel shame?' The elders all consented to his will.

    South of the pavilion runs a thoroughfare where ancient trees stand, and there in their shade they raised a three-span tower. Using only the people's leisure hours from farming, they completed it in mere days. From its heights one sees blue mountains encircling all around, a clear stream flowing before, green shadows spread across the earth, and cool breezes arriving of themselves. It is truly a place of rare beauty. I beseech you to grant this tower a name and compose a record to bring honor to our county."

    I replied: "How dare I, with my meager talent, presume to name it? Yet when I hear the name Biok, I cannot help but be moved. For I have long heard that in the age of Yao and Shun, every household was worthy of enfeoffment. We scholars, born into this world and schooled from youth in the words of sages, all harbor the aspiration to govern as Yao and Shun governed—yet who among us has truly accomplished this? What is the reason? The way of Yao and Shun is nothing but benevolence and righteousness, which are the inherent principles of the human heart. All people possess this heart; all hearts contain these principles. We merely fail to exhaust them fully. When a ruler above exhausts his heart and ministers below exhaust theirs, and when ruler and ministers meet in perfect accord—this has been rare since ancient times.

    But you, sir, come from the house of Biok and have long known its name—your aspiration to embody the governance of Yao and Shun runs deep. Having met these auspicious times and risen to the imperial court through merit, charged with the responsibility of remonstrance, you have earned the sovereign's profound regard. Your future duties shall surely be great. Should you one day, with the heart of a Yao and Shun, enact policies of a Yao and Shun, and thereby grant our Eastern realm the custom where every household deserves enfeoffment, then surely it shall begin from your county. And where such custom flourishes, there too shall arise the songs sung in the streets.

    When a tower stands south of the pavilion and a thoroughfare stretches south of the tower, the people singing in those streets shall sing without ceasing. What joy shall those experience who ascend this tower and hear these songs? Why not name it the Tower of Thoroughfare Songs?"

    Park bowed and replied: "How grand! How can one so humble as I deserve this? Yet I shall convey your meaning to the elders and people of my home, and keep it forever in my heart."

    I am old now and cannot exhaust my own heart as I should. Yet having given the tower its name, I am moved anew to record these words.
  footnotes:
    - Yao and Shun were legendary sage-kings of ancient China whose virtuous rule was so complete that all people lived in harmony, making each household worthy of being enfeoffed as a noble.
    - The phrase 'songs sung in the streets' (康衢之謠) echoes the ancient Chinese belief that peaceful governance produces spontaneous songs of joy from the people.
    - 'The ''Tower of Thoroughfare Songs'' (衢謠) serves as a double meaning: both referring to the literal street below and to the ideal of harmonious governance that produces the people''s natural expressions of contentment.'
